t3910.text: Keep in mind that these are completely separate incidents. All of them were done by different drivers. This is certainly not a one time thing. As I said before, I have to account for in my routine so I’m not late.

t3911.text: When I told this guy he was breaking the law, he said: “no I’m not. Get a taxi. Uber drivers don’t have to let dogs in.” This guy did eventually let me in as well but he made it obvious that he wasn’t happy about it.

t3912.text: Oh and there was yet another driver who I had to convince to let me in. I couldn’t get another Uber because I was in a rush to get a train. If I waited any longer, I might of missed it.

t3913.text: Another driver wouldn’t let me in because: “the dog isn’t allowed in here. It’s up to me.” He did eventually let me in but only after I said he was breaking the law. I had to stand there arguing my case for ages.

t3914.text: Also, the car and license plate matched the description in the app. I had a sighted friend with me who was able to confirm this. Oh and then there was the driver who said: “oh you’re blind” and just drove off.

t3915.text: That was a flat out lie because he didn’t have anybody else in his car. If he really was waiting for Emily, why did he take off without her? If she was real, wouldn’t she wonder where the hell her lift went?

t3917.text: And before anyone comes in my mentions suggesting this, none of them said they were afraid of dogs. They gave all kinds of BS reasons. There was a driver who got there, saw my dog and said I had the wrong car and he was waiting for Emily.

t5324.text: Paragraph 131.9 includes this clear warning: “The ANAO has put an emphasis on the geographic distribution of grant activities as a measure of equitable distribution and as an indicator of party-political bias in the distribution of grants.”

t5325.text: Then there’s Part 13 which deals with Probity and Transparency: “131.3 .... decisions relating to grant opportunities are impartial; appropriately documented and reported; publicly defensible; and lawful. “

t5326.text: “The report must include a brief statement of reasons (i.e. the basis of the approval for each grant). The report must be provided to the Finance Minister by 31 March each year for the preceding calendar year.”

t5327.text: “bf. Ministers ... must report annually to the Finance Minister on all instances where they have decided to approve a particular grant which the relevant official has recommended be rejected.”

t5328.text: “bb. (the Minister) must record, in writing, the basis for the approval relative to the grant opportunity guidelines and the key principle of achieving value with relevant money” And ....

t5329.text: “41.10. ... the Minister: ba. must not approve the grant without first receiving written advice from officials on the merits of the proposed grant or group of grants. “ and ....
